{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609620","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609620"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:48:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:48:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16109"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16109","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16109"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0,0.96,0,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8800"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74152"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8800","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8800"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16109"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59643"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"7615"},{"type":"tags","id":"8689"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21005"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21008"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74152"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring embryonic development, the undifferentiated gonad can develop into either testes or ovaries. This fate decision depends on specific genetic factors.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the role of SRY in gonadal development?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Promotes ovarian differentiation","Suppresses all gonadal development","Triggers testis development","Required for both ovary and testis formation","Maintains the undifferentiated gonadal state"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that SRY \u003Cstrong\u003Etriggers testis development\u003C/strong\u003E. When present, the SRY gene initiates a cascade of molecular events that direct the bipotential gonad to develop into testes. In its absence, the gonad follows the default female developmental pathway.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPromotes ovarian differentiation\u003C/strong\u003E - SRY specifically promotes male, not female, gonadal development\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuppresses all gonadal development\u003C/strong\u003E - Rather than suppressing development, SRY actively promotes testis formation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequired for both ovary and testis formation\u003C/strong\u003E - Only testis development requires SRY; ovaries develop in its absence\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaintains the undifferentiated gonadal state\u003C/strong\u003E - SRY actively promotes differentiation rather than maintaining an undifferentiated state\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the absence of SRY, genes such as WNT4 and FOXL2 direct the development of ovarian tissue, which requires the presence of germ cells for proper formation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The SRY gene on the Y chromosome triggers male sex determination by initiating testis development.","In the absence of SRY, ovarian development proceeds as the default developmental pathway.","Ovarian development requires specific genes like WNT4 and FOXL2, along with the presence of germ cells."],"references":["Larney C, Bailey 